Data Access

# read webpage for Grammy Awards
webpage <- read_html("https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grammy_Award_for_Record_of_the_Year")

# copy xpath for table of 1980s to 2010s
XPATH1980 <- '/html/body/div[3]/div[3]/div[5]/div[1]/table[5]'
XPATH1990 <- '/html/body/div[3]/div[3]/div[5]/div[1]/table[6]'
XPATH2000 <- '/html/body/div[3]/div[3]/div[5]/div[1]/table[7]'
XPATH2010 <- '/html/body/div[3]/div[3]/div[5]/div[1]/table[8]'

# create tables of songs from 1980s to 2010s
table_1980 <- webpage %>%
  html_nodes(xpath = XPATH1980) %>%
  html_table(fill = TRUE)
d1980 <- table_1980[[1]]

table_1990 <- webpage %>%
  html_nodes(xpath = XPATH1990) %>%
  html_table(fill = TRUE)
d1990 <- table_1990[[1]]

table_2000 <- webpage %>%
  html_nodes(xpath = XPATH2000) %>%
  html_table(fill = TRUE)
d2000 <- table_2000[[1]]

table_2010 <- webpage %>%
  html_nodes(xpath = XPATH2010) %>%
  html_table(fill = TRUE)
d2010 <- table_2010[[1]]

Data Wrangling

# join tables of 4 years together, and remove the NAs
table_1980to1990 <- d1980 %>%
  full_join(d1990)
Joining, by = c("Year[I]", "Record", "Artist(s)", "Production team")
table_1980to2000 <- table_1980to1990 %>%
  full_join(d2000)
Joining, by = c("Year[I]", "Record", "Artist(s)", "Production team")
table_1980to2019 <- table_1980to2000 %>%
  full_join(d2010) %>%
  na.omit()
Joining, by = c("Year[I]", "Record", "Artist(s)", "Production team")
# remove column Production team which   will not be used
table_1980to2019$`Production team` <- NULL

# rename the variables
names(table_1980to2019) <- c("year","track","artist")

# change entries in the year column to only contain specific years
table_1980to2019$year <- substr(table_1980to2019$year,1,4)

data set with all lyrics, separate the words

verse_words <- lyrics1980to2019 %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, lyric)

data set without stop_word and 11 words

# filter out stop_words
ft <- verse_words %>%
  anti_join(stop_words)
Joining, by = "word"
# filter out the 11 words
ft_stop_11 <- ft %>%
  filter(!word %in% c("ba", "du", "yeah", "da", "ya", "ooh", "gonna", "na", "uh", "la", "hol"))

Code explanation

To create the data frame of filtered out stop words (stop_words and the 11 words), I first need to get the raw data from Wikipedia, by getting the xpaths for tables of four decades, and create four data frames correspondingly. Then I joined them together one by one using function full_join() with the NAs removed using function na.omit(). After that, I removed the unwanted column Production team by using the NULL command. Then I renamed the variables to year, track, and artist" by using names() <- c() command. To remove the brackets in the year column, I used substr() to only preserve the first 4 characters. Now, I added the lyrics using add_genius(). To filter out the unwanted words, I first separate the lyrics into rows for each word, then I used function anti_join() to remove words in stop_wrods, and then I filtered out those unwanted 11 words by using filter(!word %in% c()), then the final data frame will have the remaining words in rows.

Graph 1

lyrics1980to2019_80sto10s_3variables %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = decade, y = n, fill = decade))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  labs(x = "Decade", y = "Words per Song", title = "Boxplots of Words per Grammy Nominated Song by Decade")

Interpretation: This graph compared the number of words for each song that was nominated in the Grammy Awards in each decade. We can see the graph shows 4 boxplots for 4 decades, each colored region represents the middle 50% of words per song in each decade, with the line inside it showing the median of words per song in that decade, the lower and upper 25% are shown by straight lines, and outliers are shown in dots. For example, the 2000s has the widest range of words per song, while the 1990s has the least median of words per song and the smallest middle 50%, but the 1990s has the most outliers that some songs have a large number of words. Overall, the words per song are increasing in terms of minimum, median, and the 25th percentile from the 1990s to 2010s.

lyrics1980to2019_80sto10s_filtered_sentiments_1_0 <- lyrics1980to2019_80sto10s_filtered_sentiments %>%
  mutate(sentiment_score = case_when(.$sentiment == "positive" ~ 1, .$sentiment=="negative" ~ 0))

find the net sentiment by filtering out negative sentiment

lyrics1980to2019_80sto10s_filtered_sentiments_1_0_net <- lyrics1980to2019_80sto10s_filtered_sentiments_1_0 %>%
  filter(sentiment_score == "1")

Graph 4

ggplot(lyrics1980to2019_80sto10s_filtered_sentiments_1_0_net) +

  geom_bar() +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Net Sentiment", title = "Net Sentiment Score by Year") +
  scale_x_discrete(breaks=c(1980, 1985, 1990, 1995, 2000, 2005, 2010, 2015, 2020), labels=c("1980", "", "1990", "", "2000", "", "2010", "", "2020"))

Interpretation: This bar chart used the data frame of filtered words in lyrics of songs nominated by the Grammy Award with sentiment added, and changed negative sentiment to sentiment score 0, positive to 1. Then the net sentiment score is available and shown for each year with one color showing a decade from 1980 to 2019. For example, by looking at the graph, the year 1989 has the highest net sentiment score that is above 60, which means there are above 60 positive words used than negative words used in 1989.

5

get the mean sentiment for each decade

mean80s <- sum(lyrics1980to2019_80sto10s_filtered_sentiments_1_0[lyrics1980to2019_80sto10s_filtered_sentiments_1_0$decade == "1980s", "sentiment_score"])/10

mean90s <- sum(lyrics1980to2019_80sto10s_filtered_sentiments_1_0[lyrics1980to2019_80sto10s_filtered_sentiments_1_0$decade == "1990s", "sentiment_score"])/10

mean00s <- sum(lyrics1980to2019_80sto10s_filtered_sentiments_1_0[lyrics1980to2019_80sto10s_filtered_sentiments_1_0$decade == "2000s", "sentiment_score"])/10

mean10s <- sum(lyrics1980to2019_80sto10s_filtered_sentiments_1_0[lyrics1980to2019_80sto10s_filtered_sentiments_1_0$decade == "2010s", "sentiment_score"])/10

create a new data frame with mean for each decade

mean_senti <- c(mean80s, mean90s, mean00s, mean10s)
decade <- c("1980s", "1990s", "2000s", "2010s")
table_mean_senti <- data.frame(mean_senti, decade)

Graph 5

ggplot(table_mean_senti) +
  aes(x = decade, weight = mean_senti, fill = decade) +
  geom_bar() +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  labs(x = "Decade", y = "Mean Sentiment Score", title = "Mean Sentiment Score by Decade")

Interpretation: This bar chart shows the mean sentiment score by decade for filtered words in lyrics of songs that are nominated by the Grammy Award. The mean sentiment score is calculated by dividing the sum of the sentiment score for all songs in a decade by 10 years. From the graph, we can see the 1980s has the highest mean sentiment score, meaning the 1980s used the most positive words on average from 1980 to 2019. From the 1990s to the 2010s, there is an increasing trend in mean sentiment score.

Graph 6

ggplot(lyrics1980to2019_80sto10s_filtered_sentiments_1_0_net_yearly_80sto10s) +
  aes(x = year, y = sentiment, color = decade) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(aes(group = 1), se=F) +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Net Sentiment", title = "Net Sentiment Score by Year of Grammy Nominated Records from 1980 - 2019 with Linear Model Fit") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size=10)) +
  scale_x_discrete(breaks=c(1980, 1985, 1990, 1995, 2000, 2005, 2010, 2015, 2020), labels=c("1980", "", "1990", "", "2000", "", "2010", "", "2020"))

Interpretation: This is a scatter plot integrated with a linear regression model of net sentiment score by year of Grammy Award nominated records from 1980 to 2019. The data frame used for this graph is created by getting the sum of the sentiment score of each year. The year is represented as x coordinate, and the net sentiment score is represented as y coordinate, for example, the year 1990 has the net sentiment score 10. Looking at the graph, the linear model is fluctuant, from the year 1980 to the year 2000 has a decreasing trend, then from the year 2000 to the year 2019, there is an increasing trend shown.
